// @test: typecheck-pass
// @level: L0
// @tier: 0
// @tags: modules, glob, import-origin, shadowing, vuva-mod-med-2
// @description: VVA #146 / MOD-MED-2 — glob-vs-glob origin discipline.
//
// When two glob mounts both export a name, the legacy behaviour was
// "second-encountered wins" — source-text-position-dependent and
// observably non-deterministic across `mount` reorders. The fix
// tags every glob-imported name with its `ImportOrigin` (Stdlib /
// External / Project) and resolves conflicts via a total ordering:
//
//   Project > External > Stdlib
//
// Same-origin ties go to the first registrant for determinism.
//
// This test is the lightweight smoke: a single-file project that
// declares a local type and uses it. Without the arbiter, an
// inadvertent stdlib-glob clash on a short name (e.g. `Tree` later
// added to core/) would silently swap the user's type for the
// stdlib's. With the arbiter, the project type always wins; the
// user gets a `W_STDLIB_SHADOW` warning if they actually evicted
// a stdlib entry, but the build succeeds with their definition
// active.

type LocalTree<T> is Leaf(T) | Branch { left: Heap<LocalTree<T>>, right: Heap<LocalTree<T>> };

fn main() {
    print("project-wins");
}
